# Subject-matter docs

> **What this is**: cumulative-knowledge index for this install — one doc per topic, grown over time.
> **How to read**: scan this index, click into whatever's relevant. Each doc is self-contained with cross-links.
> **How to write**: see "Editing the tree" below.

## Why this folder exists

Journals (`_context/<scope>/journal/<YYYY-MM-DD>.md`) capture what happened **chronologically**.
This folder captures what we know **by subject**. They complement each other:

| Need | Look at |
|---|---|
| "What did we do yesterday" | Today's journal in the active scope |
| "What did we learn this week" | Recent journal entries across scopes |
| "What's true RIGHT NOW about X" | The topic doc for X here |
| "Where did the knowledge about X come from" | The topic doc's `Source history` section |

If a journal entry contains a meaningful piece of state ("X is now true"), the topic doc gets updated.
If the journal entry is just a step on the way ("tried Y, didn't work"), it stays in the journal only.

## Status legend

Each doc declares its status in its header:

| Status | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `active` | Currently true; consult freely; update when state changes. |
| `experimental` | Hypothesis or in-progress idea. May change or be abandoned. |
| `deprecated` | Was true; isn't anymore; kept for context. |
| `reference-only` | Process docs, templates, protocols. Doesn't describe runtime state. |

Inside an otherwise-active doc, speculative claims are flagged inline with `> [SPECULATIVE]` and no-longer-true sections with `> [DEPRECATED]`.

## The tree

(populate this table as you create topic docs)

| Tier | Topic | Status | What it covers |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | (add your first topic doc here) | active | (one-line description) |

## Editing the tree

**Any chat can create, edit, or promote a doc.** No permission gates.

When you learn something worth capturing as state:

1. Find the relevant topic doc (or create a new one).
2. Update the `What we know` section, then bump `Last reviewed`.
3. If you ADD a new doc, list it in the table above and link it from any sibling that references it.
4. Mention the new/changed doc in your scope's journal for that day so other chats notice it.

### When to promote a section to its own file

A section earns its own file when it starts having **sub-items of its own**, not just when it gets long.

### Template

Copy this when creating a new doc:

```markdown
# <Topic name>

> **What this is**: 1-sentence definition.
> **Status**: active / experimental / deprecated / reference-only
> **Last reviewed**: YYYY-MM-DD

## TL;DR

2-4 sentences for quick scanning.

## Why it matters

Why this topic exists.

## What we know

Cumulative state of knowledge with subsections as needed.

## Open questions / unresolved

Threads to pick up. Delete if N/A.

## Related topics

Cross-links to siblings.

## Source history

- YYYY-MM-DD — where this knowledge came from (journal ref, decoder run, manual investigation, etc.)
```

